news.headline: What 'mNAV' Really Means for Bitcoin Treasury Companies — and Where It Falls Short
news.summary: Most common valuation yardstick is the mNAV. It compares a firm's market cap plus debt minus any cash to the market value of its bitcoin holdings. A reading above 1.0 implies the market is putting a premium on the company's BTC treasury.
news.article_text:
The most common valuation yardstick is the mNAV. It compares a company's enterprise value (EV) — which is a firm's market cap plus debt minus any cash — to the market value of its bitcoin holdings. This provides investors with a means to evaluate the extent to which the market assigns a premium or discount to its treasury.

The metric is now widely followed. Strategy publishes its own mNAV on its investor site, while third-party dashboards such as BitcoinTreasuries.net track various mNAV figures

news.headline: Zscaler Slides Despite Strong Quarter
news.summary: Zscaler (NASDAQ:ZS) shares slid about 6% even though the company just posted a strong quarter and raised its outlook. Zscaler earned $0.96 per share on revenue of $788.1 million, beating forecasts.
news.article_text:
This article first appeared on GuruFocus.

Zscaler (NASDAQ:ZS) shares slid about 6% even though the company just posted a strong quarter and raised its outlook, a classic case of Wall Street shrugging at good news.

For the quarter ending Oct. 31, Zscaler earned $0.96 per share on revenue of $788.1 million, beating forecasts of $0.86 and $773.9 million. Sales jumped 26% from a year earlier, a clear sign that businesses are still investing in cybersecurity even as other tech spending slows.

news.headline: What 'mNAV' Really Means for Bitcoin Treasury Companies — and Where It Falls Short
news.summary: Most common valuation yardstick is the mNAV. It compares a firm's market cap plus debt minus any cash to the market value of its bitcoin holdings. A reading above 1.0 implies the market is putting a premium on the company's BTC treasury.
news.article_text:
The most common valuation yardstick is the mNAV. It compares a company's enterprise value (EV) — which is a firm's market cap plus debt minus any cash — to the market value of its bitcoin holdings. This provides investors with a means to evaluate the extent to which the market assigns a premium or discount to its treasury.

The metric is now widely followed. Strategy publishes its own mNAV on its investor site, while third-party dashboards such as BitcoinTreasuries.net track various mNAV figures

news.headline: Michael Saylor Sunday Change-Up Suggests New Announcement Coming Monday
news.summary: Strategy, the largest publicly traded corporate holder of bitcoin with nearly 650,000 BTC, has seen its stock price crumble. Some believe green dots could signal stock buybacks or balance sheet shifts, while others wonder if it's a hint about possible bitcoin sales.
news.article_text:
For the past twelve months, Strategy (MSTR) Executive Chairman Michael Saylor has maintained a consistent pattern, making a playful X post nearly every Sunday using a chart with orange dots to suggest a Monday announcement of additional bitcoin BTC $ 85,998.66 purchases.



The pattern appeared to break at least a little bit this Sunday, though, with Saylor posting the same chart, but saying, "what if we start adding green dots."
